Customer response to Bank marketing campaign: To be or Not to be? It is a prediction.

Posted on 2020-10-29 In Predictive Modelling Views:

Customer propensity predictive models are one of the most common preditive models in Data mining for Customer insights. It is a very powerful tool to predict Customer responses as well as Customer response probabilities for certain Customer engagement activities, like Marketing Campaigns, based on labeled historical data using features like Customer demographics, Customer behaviours, and Customer engagement stats etc. Then the predicted Customer response probability can be used to design marketing campaigns so as to improve marketing campaign effectiveness and increase ROI. Moreover, the relationships between selected features and target Customer response identified from the predictive analysis also have great business value. The insights of these relationships can be used to gain deep understanding of Customers and enable business to better serve Customers through offerings.

In this blog, I looked into a specific use case in Banking industry and carried out predictive modelling and analysis based on a open banking dataset to predict which Customers are more likely to subscribe Bank Term Deposit using CatBoost. If you are interested in knowing more about CatBoost machine learning, you can refer to my previous blog which briefly talked about it.

Data

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to access if the product (bank term deposit) would be (or not) subscribed.
This open bank marketing campaign dataset can be downloaded from UCI data repository. The full dataset was described and analyzed in [Moro et al., 2011].
This banking dataset has variables below.

  • Bank client data:
    1. age (numeric)
    2. job : type of job (categorical)
    3. marital : marital status (categorical)
    4. education (categorical)
    5. default: has credit in default? (binary: yes,no)
    6. balance: average yearly balance, in euros (numeric)
    7. housing: has housing loan? (binary: yes,no)
    8. loan: has personal loan? (binary: yes,no)
  • Related with the last contact of the current campaign:
    1. contact: contact communication type (categorical)
    2. day: last contact day of the month (numeric)
    3. month: last contact month of year (categorical)
    4. duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric)
  • Other attributes:
    1. campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)
    2. pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric, -1 means client was not previously contacted)
    3. previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric)
    4. poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical)
  • Target variable:
    1. y: has the client subscribed a term deposit? (binary: yes,no)

Problem Statement

Term deposits allow banks to hold onto a deposit for a specific amount of time, so banks can invest in higher gain financial products to make a profit. In addition, banks also hold better chance to persuade term deposit clients into buying other products such as funds or insurance to further increase their revenues. As a result, the Portuguese bank would like to identify existing clients that have higher chance to subscribe for a term deposit and focus marketing effort on such clients.

Objective: Develop a classification model to predict whether a Customer will subscribe the bank term deposit or not, and also the likelihood.

EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis)

There are some great insights from EDA:

  • Job: retired, student, unemployed and management are more likely to subscribe term deposit. While blue-collar and entrepreneur are less likely to subscribe; Interesting, there are some counter-intuitive insights here, like I wouldnt expect unemployed clients would be into term deposit bank product. Wouldnt they have more tight spending on money?

  • Education: The higher the education of clients, the more likely to subscribe; The higher educated clients may have higher financial knowledge and literace, hence more confident into term deposit?

  • Marital: Single clients more likely to subscribe; Interesting.

  • Contact: if contacted to Mobile, clients more likely to subscribe; hmm why?

  • poutcome: Clients who has previous successful marketing campaign more likely to subscribe. This is intuitive as past successful campaign may lead to next one;

  • Month & Day: Mar, Apr, Sep, Oct got higher likelyhood, and there are certain days in the Month will have higher likelihood to subscribe. It is worth but not covered in this analysis that to transform day in a month to weekdays to further identify the pattern/insights;

  • default, housing, loan: The clients with no credit in default, with no housing loan, and with no personal loan more likely to subscribe to term deposit; This is also very intuitive since clients without loans or defaults tends to have more free money to invest into term deposit;

  • duration: The clients subscribed tend to have longer call duration; This makes sense as more communication may drive the behaviour of purchase?

  • balance: The clients with more average yearly balance more likely to subscribe term deposit. This is intuitive since more balance means more flexible money to invest;

  • Age: From 20s to 30s, as working age increases, the clients likelihood to subscribe also increases. Then stablise from 30s to 60s, which are the main working ages. After 60s, it starts to fluctuate a lot. This could be due to small sample size. It maybe worth to look at Age and Job cross analysis at the same time, but this is not covered in this blog;

Predictive Modelling

I have used CatBoost to develop classification model to predict the target variable in this specific case. CatBoost handles the categorical features/variable very conveniently.

Model Validation & Performance

The model achieved ROC AUC=0.937 on splitted testing dataset, which is pretty good performance.

Feature Importance


From the feature importance plot, we can see that Call duration plays the most significant role in predicting Customer response on term deposit subscription. Month and Day of marketing campaign, and also Contact whether call to mobile or telephone gives Bank actionable insights to better design the campaign activities. The Customer demographic variables, especially balance and age have more significance in targeting clients that are more likely to subscribe.

Final thoughts

This sums up for the blog post, there are some very interesting Customer insights that can be used by the Bank to better targeting clients on marketing campaigns. Those also trigger the drill to understand deeper on Customer why these relationship would occur. For example, we know that the behavior of clients having longer call durations may lead to higher chance of subscribing, but we cannot exactly know why or what their motivations are. In other words, we identified features on what customers are doing, instead of what they are thinking.
This will be the differentiation between Big Data and Small Data. Small data plays a critical role in answering Why questions and capturing Customer motivations and Emotions. I will be writing a blog to illustrate more on the idea and difference between Big and Small data concepts. Stay tuned!
